Just now

--

Pure Idle has no artist. It never did. I cannot draw, and for a game I hoped to sell cheaply I had no budget to commission art or buy asset packs. So I made a decision at the very start that shaped everything you see on screen: there would be no images. Every star, every building, the black hole at the center of the game, and the great flashes of collapse and rebirth are not pictures loaded from a file. They are drawn, live, sixty times a second, in JavaScript on an HTML5 Canvas, out of nothing but math.
This part of the series is about that surface — the part players actually look at — and how a constraint (no art) quietly turned into the game’s whole visual identity.
You can read the first part of this article here.
Author: Aleksei Makarenko. Pen names: Alex Vuorenmaa, Riven Elow.
