A building is not a picture. It is a polygon
Start with the production grid, because it is the clearest example. In Pure Idle every building type has a shape: the Star Collector is a circle, the Energy Siphon a diamond, the Mass Forge a square, the Essence Crucible a hexagon. A player reads the factory by silhouette. And not one of those shapes is an image. They are all the same drawing function, called with a different number of sides:
_drawShape(ctx, x, y, r, typeId, shape, color, fillAlpha, strokeAlpha) {
ctx.beginPath();
switch (shape) {
case 'circle': this._pathCircle(ctx, x, y, r); break;
case 'diamond': this._pathPolygon(ctx, x, y, r, 4, Math.PI/4); break; // square, rotated 45°
case 'square': this._pathPolygon(ctx, x, y, r * 0.85, 4, 0); break;
case 'hexagon': this._pathPolygon(ctx, x, y, r, 6, 0); break;
case 'triangle': this._pathPolygon(ctx, x, y, r, 3, -Math.PI/2); break;
case 'octagon': this._pathPolygon(ctx, x, y, r, 8, Math.PI/8); break;
// …
}
// then fill and stroke with the building's colour
}A diamond is a four-sided polygon turned forty-five degrees. A hexagon is the same call with a `6` where the `4` was. Once you have one function that walks a number of points around a circle, you have every regular shape in the game for free. This is the whole philosophy in miniature: I did not draw a dozen building icons, I wrote one small routine and passed it different numbers. There is no reason to hand-draw what geometry will hand you.
The center of the screen: a black hole made of gradients
The heart of the main scene is the gate — the black hole you pour stars into. It looks, I hope, like something with depth and weight. It is, underneath, a stack of translucent radial gradients painted on top of each other, tinted differently depending on how far the player has progressed:
const grad = ctx.createRadialGradient(cx, cy, 0, cx, cy, maxR);
if (stage >= 5) { // late game: violet void
grad.addColorStop(0, '#1e0e30');
grad.addColorStop(0.3, '#120820');
grad.addColorStop(1, '#030108');
} else if (stage >= 2) { // early game: warm amber
grad.addColorStop(0, '#161008');
grad.addColorStop(1, '#060302');
}
ctx.fillStyle = grad;
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);A radial gradient is just a fill that fades from one colour at a point to another at a radius — bright in the middle, black at the edge. Layer a few of them, add a slow drift of particles spiralling toward the center, and a flat rectangle of pixels reads as a bottomless well. There is no 3D here, no lighting engine, no texture. There is the oldest trick in painting — dark around a glow makes the glow feel deep — expressed in five lines of Canvas code.
The sky grows as you play
Here is a design decision I am fonder of than any single effect. The background of Pure Idle is not fixed. It grows with the player. Early on the sky is nearly empty. As you unlock technologies, galaxy arms appear, then nebulae, then comets, pulsars, an aurora, streams of light bending toward the black hole. The render code says this out loud — each layer is gated behind how much you have unlocked:
const techCount = this.game.techTree.getUnlockedCount();
if (techCount >= 1) this.drawGalaxyArms(techCount);
if (techCount >= 6) this.drawNebulae(techCount);
if (this.comets.length > 0) this.drawComets();
if (stage >= 5) this.drawAurora();
if (this.game.techTree.isUnlocked('gravity1')) this.drawGravityLines();
if (this.game.techTree.isUnlocked('magnetism')) this.drawSpiralStreams();This turns the visuals themselves into a reward. In Part 3 I was hard on the technology tree for being mostly multipliers — and it is. But this is the place where unlocking a node does something you can see. Buy into gravity, and lines of force appear in the sky, curving toward the center. The number in the corner going up is abstract; the sky filling with structure is not. For a genre that runs on abstract numbers, giving progress a visible face is one of the few things that reliably makes it feel like more than arithmetic.
The big moments: collapse, supernova, crisis
Idle games need set-piece moments — the instant you reset everything and the screen rewards you for it. In Pure Idle these are collapse and ascension (the two prestige resets from Part 2), plus a supernova and a crisis event tied to late upgrades. Every one of them is built from the same two cheap ingredients: a burst of particles, and a shake of the screen.
The shake is almost embarrassingly simple. Something asks the background to tremble for a number of frames at some intensity, and the render loop offsets the whole canvas by a shrinking random amount:
triggerShake(intensity, frames) {
this.shakeFrames = frames;
this._shakeIntensity = intensity;
}The collapse effect is a ring of particles that rush inward as the run implodes into dark energy — sixty little points, scattered around the center, animated toward it:
const particles = [];
for (let i = 0; i < 60; i++) {
const a = Math.random() * Math.PI * 2; // random angle
const d = 50 + Math.random() * Math.min(cx, cy) * 0.6; // random distance out
particles.push({
ox: cx + Math.cos(a) * d,
oy: cy + Math.sin(a) * d,
s: 1 + Math.random() * 2,
h: Math.random() * 60–30 + 15, // slight colour spread
});
}
this._prestigeAnim = { type: 'collapse', t: 0, dur: 120, particles, cx, cy };That is the entire spectacle: sixty dots, a screen shake, a floating number telling you what you gained. And it works — the player feels the weight of the reset. I learned this lesson on my first game, an interactive novel, where three lines of code — a vertical screen jolt and a red flash for a fraction of a second — could make a punch in the text land in the reader’s body. The principle carried straight over: a convincing “big moment” is not expensive art. It is a little motion, timed well, at the instant the player did something meaningful. The brain fills in the rest.
Connections, and a warehouse drawn as a triangle
Two more things on screen are worth naming, because they show the same approach reaching into every corner.
The production buildings are joined by connections, and those are drawn as lines with small particles travelling along them, so you can watch a resource physically move from producer to consumer — path plotted point to point with the same `moveTo` / `lineTo` primitives everything else uses.
And the warehouse — the RPG-like subsystem that is the whole subject of the next part — is rendered as a triangular field of hexagons: a row of one, then two, then three, widening downward. That triangle is not a background image either; it is computed, hex by hex, and drawn as outlined polygons, the same way the buildings are. When I wanted the shape to feel less cramped, I did not open an image editor — I changed the spacing and the frame in code and re-ran it, again and again, until it sat right.
Why draw everything in code
It would be easy to present “no artist, so I drew it all in code” as pure hardship. It was hard. But it also handed me things a folder of sprites never would.
Everything shares one visual language automatically, because everything is drawn by the same handful of routines with the same palette — a building, a star, and a warehouse hex are all outlined polygons with a translucent fill and a coloured stroke. Nothing needs re-exporting when I change a colour; I change one value and the whole game shifts with it. It scales to any screen size without blurring, because a shape redrawn at a new radius is simply sharp at that radius — there is no fixed-resolution image to stretch. And there is no asset pipeline at all: no importing, no packing, no versioning of art files. For one person working in the evenings, removing an entire category of work from the project was worth more than any single pretty sprite would have been.
The constraint chose the style, and the style turned out to fit a game about stars and geometry and numbers climbing in the dark. A clicker about the cosmos, drawn entirely in the language of circles and gradients and points of light, has a coherence I could not have bought.
The next part goes inside the one system that breaks the clicker’s own mold — the warehouse, where I built a small role-playing game, with named workers who gain levels, stats, and equipment, sitting quietly inside a game about dropping stars into a black hole.
